## PLAN AMENDMENT (incorporated for gate attempt 2 — all 4 seats converge)
1. validateSHA enforces FULL 40/64 lowercase hex (mirror refstore.validateOID): rejects empty, leading-dash, non-hex, short prefixes, AND mutable names like 'main'/'HEAD' -> ErrInvalidSHA. (A recorded manifest git_sha is ALWAYS a full OID, so this is correct; it guarantees replay never checks out a moving ref.) The leading-dash rejection is now a subset (kept for a clear message).
2. After 'git rev-parse --verify <sha>^{commit}', REVALIDATE the resolved output is a full OID and pass THAT captured OID (never the raw input) to 'git worktree add --detach -- <dir> <oid>' (note the '--' separator). Make 'uses captured OID' an explicit invariant + test.
3. API: Cleanup(ctx) error is primary; Close() is the io.Closer/defer-friendly wrapper that calls Cleanup(context.Background()) (documented: no cancellation, appropriate for cleanup). Both idempotent; calling Close after an explicit Cleanup is a no-op (swallow 'not a working tree' rc=128 + RemoveAll-of-missing as success).
4. On 'worktree add' failure: RemoveAll the temp dir THEN 'worktree prune' to clear partial registration.
5. Tests add: branch-name/'main'/short-sha input -> ErrInvalidSHA (proves no moving-ref checkout); resolved-OID invariant; idempotent Close-after-Cleanup no-op.
6. Docstring: clarify 'root' is the repo root for 'git -C'; temp dir via os.MkdirTemp("") in the system temp dir (outside the repo).
## Plan gate (attempt 2) — Tier 1 four-seat: BLOCK (3 GO / 1 BLOCK)
- Claude Opus: GO (empirically validated); Gemini Pro: GO; pi/pilms: GO; GPT-5.5 xhigh (codex): BLOCK — two subtle valid catches:
  1. Full 40/64-hex validateSHA is NOT sufficient: in a SHA-1 repo a 64-hex string (or in SHA-256 a 40-hex string) can be a BRANCH NAME that rev-parse resolves to a moving tip; capturing the resolved OID merely freezes that unsafe resolution. REQUIRED: require resolvedOID == inputSHA (input must BE the commit OID, not just resolve to one) + a regression test for a hex-looking ref of the other width.
  2. Cleanup ordering remove->prune->RemoveAll can leave stale .git/worktrees metadata if 'worktree remove' fails but the filesystem delete succeeds. REQUIRED: prune AFTER RemoveAll.

## PLAN AMENDMENT (incorporated for gate attempt 3)
1. After 'git rev-parse --verify <sha>^{commit}' -> resolvedOID, REQUIRE resolvedOID == inputSHA (both lowercase full hex; rev-parse emits lowercase). If they differ, the input resolved to something other than itself (a hex-looking branch/tag/mismatched-width ref) -> reject with ErrInvalidSHA. This guarantees the input IS the recorded commit OID, immune to hex-looking moving refs in either object format. (Legitimate recorded git_sha is a direct commit OID, so equality always holds.)
2. Cleanup ordering: 'git worktree remove --force <dir>' -> os.RemoveAll(dir) -> 'git worktree prune' (prune runs LAST so it reaps any admin entry left when remove failed but the dir was deleted). Idempotent + no-leak preserved.
3. Tests add: a branch named with 64-hex chars in a SHA-1 repo (and/or a tag whose name/oid is hex) -> ErrInvalidSHA via the resolvedOID==input guard (proves no moving-ref/peeled-tag checkout); a cleanup case where 'remove' is forced to fail but RemoveAll+prune still leaves no stale .git/worktrees entry.
## Plan gate (attempt 3) — Tier 1 four-seat: PASS 4/4 GO
- Gemini Pro: GO; Claude Opus: GO (both holes closed; 40-hex-name-in-SHA1 edge is a minor error-semantics nit, still safely rejected as ErrSHANotFound); pi/pilms: GO; GPT-5.5 xhigh (codex): GO.
Converged after 2 BLOCK rounds (full-hex validateSHA + Close/Cleanup; then resolvedOID==input + prune-after-RemoveAll).
Optionals folded into Implement: TrimSpace resolved OID before == compare; cleanup test inspects BOTH 'git worktree list --porcelain' AND .git/worktrees/ absence; pin the 40-hex-name-in-SHA1 ambiguity test (accept ErrSHANotFound); swallow prune errors on the add-failure path symmetrically; (cheap) same-width OID-named-ref regression; MkdirTemp prefix 'etude-worktree-*'.

ACCEPTANCE CRITERIA
Creates a throwaway worktree at the recorded git_sha, exposes its path to callers, and removes it on success and on failure. Errors clearly if the sha is missing locally. Tested for create+cleanup including the failure path.

